==English==
===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno}} / {{etyl|fro}} {{term|mercurial|lang=fro}}, and their source, {{etyl|la}} {{term|mercurialis|lang=la}}, from {{term|Mercurius||Mercury}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/məːˈkjʊəɹɪəl/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/mɝˈkjʊriəl/|/mɝˈkjɔriəl/}}, {{X-SAMPA|/m3`"kjUri@l/|/m3`kjOri@l/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{obsolete}} Any of the [[plant]]s known as [[mercury]]. {{defdate|13th-17th c.}}
# {{astrology}} Someone born under the influence of [[Mercury]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
# {{context|now|_|historical}} A perparation of mercury, especially as a treatment for [[syphilis]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# (often capitalized, see {{term|Mercurial}}) Pertaining to the [[planet]] [[Mercury]]. {{defdate|from 14th c.}}
# (often capitalized, see '''[[Mercurial]]''') Pertaining to the [[Roman]] [[god]] [[Mercury]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
# {{astrology}} Born under the influence of the planet [[Mercury]], and having such characteristics. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
# Of, or pertaining to the element [[mercury]]; containing mercury; caused by the action of mercury or [[quicksilver]]. {{defdate|from 16th c.}}
# Having a [[volatile]] or [[lively]] character; quick-witted, changeable, [[animated]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#*'''1723''', Charles Walker, ''Memoirs of Sally Salisbury'', I:
#*:From the natural '''Mercurial''' Briskness of her Temper, a sedentary Life had ever been her Aversion [...].

